text: Somewhere, baby, it's part of me, apart from me, you're laying waste to Halloween, you fucked it friend, it's on it's head, it struck the street, you're in Milwaukee, off your feet. I've been in love with the same girl since the sixth grade of high school. We were only actually together for 6 months of senior year, and those six months were the best months of my life. For all those who embrace the hook-up culture at CC, you are lying to everyone around you, and yourself. Meaningless sex will not fulfill you. A two week relationship will not fill the inadequacies you feel within you. Your stats or highest score will not make you feel better about yourself, or teach you about your sexuality. An orgasm in not love. An orgasm is animal instinct. I represent the quiet conglomerate of men who will refuse to be impressed by how much you drink, you're various piercings, how well you know how to suck a dick, how understanding you are of what you like, or how well you dance. I would rather you tell me about yourself, your favorite musician, food, movie, etc., over dinner than I would have you tell me while we're already in bed, after I had asked for your drunken consent following the 2-4 beer pong games I had won and shouted about well within your earshot, and then have you gone by the time I wake up. I love nothing more than hearing the way you sound when you let me stick my hand between your legs, but I am more enamored by how we both feel watching a movie or seeing a concert together than I am by anything that happens sexually between us. Nothing, not sex, drugs, nor rock-and-roll, can possibly feel better than loving someone and having them love you back. And if you feel nothing in moving on to the next hook-up, you probably should not have hooked-up to begin with. I am a freshman, and my older brother went to CC and graduated here in 2008. He didn't have a single meaningful relationship here his entire college career. All he can look back on is meaningless sex and disappointment. Yes, some might call us a progressive school, despite the fact that the event we've had thus far with the largest amount of school-funding included both a loosely ordained theme of ice (yes it is cold in wintertime colorado), and a schedule of which loosely-clad girls would be dancing on stage at specific times. But, are relationships really helped by our type of progression? Is the hook-up culture really something we should feel pride in? I think not. At heart, I am a romantic, and fuck this school for making me feel like I am the outcast because of that. If I am still in love with the same girl that I first fell in love with since the sixth grade, then I am more than confident that anyone reading this can relate in some small way. So fuck everyone who is tries to act any different just to fit in with this supposed culture. It is not organic, it is forced. Love is organic. Love can never be forced.
